  {
    "project_id": "2026-031",
    "name": "Agent Utilization Rate",
    "description": "% of time an agent is either assisting or available to assist with customer activity during their scheduled shift. Remaining time is internal shrinkage (coaching, team-building sessions, lunch and breaks). Also sometimes referred to as occupancy, but this is something slightly different. Data needs: total time agents are available to help or helping customers (Logged-in Time), total number of shift minutes the agents are paid to be in the contact center (Total Paid Time). Divide \"Logged-in Time\" by \"Total Paid Time\" X100 to get percentage utilization. Recommended target is often 85%, but this can be customer specific (example: if greater investment in more offline activities is desireable, the utilization rate will be lower. Consider if occupancy would also be a good metric to include in this visualization (caluclate as Total Contact Handling Time/Total Logged time X 100). Utilization is useful for balancing costs and schedule efficiency, as well as calculating shrinkage, measuring occupance assists with measureing schedule oprimization to ensure agents don't wait too long to take calls. Consider including Shrinkage in the visualization (shrinkage is measure used in planning as a \"fudge factor\" that allows for the difference between number of staff forecasted and the practical considerations of how many employees are available at a particular time). Shrinkage is any scheduled and/or unscheduled optimization/activities prohibiting employees from performing their duties. Formula is (Total Hours External Shrinkage + Total Hours of Internal Shrinkage)/Total Hours Available X100 (normally expressed as an annualized value. External shrinkage (sickness, holiday, public holidays, paid breaks, absenteeism, lateness) and Internal shrinkage (team meetings, coaching, training, 1:1 meetings, system downtime, unplanned facility breaks, time spent helping other departments, special projects)",
